  "opinion": "As an 84-year-old woman living in Kansas City, working part-time as a sales associate and holding a master's degree, I've seen many changes in how we communicate, from letters to social media. My perspective on managing fake content is shaped by a lifetime of experience, my Islamic faith emphasizing truth and integrity, and my creative nature that appreciates genuine expression. I use social media a few times weekly, mainly to stay connected with family and enjoy hobbies like cinema and photography, so I encounter fake content occasionally but not constantly. Dealing with fake content requires a balanced approach. First, I rely on my high conscientiousness to verify information before sharing or reacting. I check sources, look for credible news outlets, and sometimes ask younger family members for help, as they're more tech-savvy. My moderate openness means I'm willing to learn new tools, like fact-checking websites, but I'm cautious due to my high neuroticism, which makes me anxious about misinformation's harm. In my sales work, honesty is key, and I apply that to social media by promoting truthful interactions. I also use my creativity to share positive, authentic content from my hobbies, like photos from cycling trips, to counter fake narratives. My high agreeableness drives me to gently correct friends if I see them sharing falsehoods, but I do so respectfully, avoiding conflict. As a Muslim, I value community and truth, so I support platforms that prioritize accuracy and report fake content when I see it. Ultimately, managing fake content is about personal responsibility, education, and fostering a culture of honesty, drawing on my experiences as a mother and professional to navigate this digital age wisely.",
